  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Recent clinical findings of research at Trondheim University Hospital suggest that surgical
      correction of the nose septum in addition to volume reduction of the nose cavity may be
      beneficial in patients who suffer from both nose obstruction and obstructive sleep apnea
      syndrome(data not yet published).

      This study aims to compare nose obstruction prevalence in sleep apnea patients and the
      general population
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
